@database qboot.guide
@master qboot.guide.in
@author megacz
@$VER: qboot 1.07 (21/09/2014)



@node Intro "qboot - Introduction"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      Did you ever ask yourself a question of what is really going on
      when your Amiga boots? I'm sure that you had tuned your startup
      plenty of times, and all that was just  playing blind until the
      result  was not a Guru nor  some  cryptic  message  saying that
      something has just failed :-] .

      Just for a minute, imagine that NASA does not give a shit about
      feedback when  they launch new space shuttle. Can  you see this
      blood-freezing conversation?

      - Hey Bob! You think it  will like not  crash on us  this time?
      - I don't know Steve, cross your fingers or  better pray to God
      because currently everything goes to NIL:! 

      And  that is exactly what every  Amiga enthusiast  has to  face
      daily. You just do not know what your computer is doing. You do
      not  know if  software  started  at all  because  there  is  no
      feedback!

      Until now, I was unable to find a program that would help me to
      change this. Although, back in  2008  I did take an approach to
      fix this  inconvinience by  writing startup  replacement for my
      own needs, but there  is just one problem  with it. It is coded
      totally in C with no script support and so not easy to alter...

      Happily there is  'qboot' which is one such nifty prog that you
      can insert  into your startup  at any point and get the view of
      what is  currently being executed on separate screen along with
      the result. This way you can  finally pinpoint problems and fix
      them.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



@node Feat "qboot - Features"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      Currently 'qboot' is (capable of):

        * Opening feedback screen that is all user definable. Options
        include: modeid,  resolution, depth,  monitor, range, display
        flags, custom font.

        * Working in twin-monitor mode so that boot console is mapped
        across  different monitor drivers. Dblscan and  CGX/P96 board
        users friendly!

        * Detecting automatically additional monitors/graphics boards
        that are initialised in the startup.

        * Installing  nice animated  logo in  top-left  corner of the
        console. Multimedia machine or not ;-) ?

        * Installing  screen bar  trigger which  allows to  show/hide
        screen bar by clicking  LMB  in top-left  corner. By  default
        screen bar is hidden.

        * Echoing command  back as found in the script along with the
        line number so you know what went wrong and where.

        * Offering  colored output which includes: resident commands,
        user  resident commands,  disk commands,  false conditionals,
        background processes output.

        * Utilising user defined colors and/or styles that are normal
        ESC  sequences. The palette is  ANSI  like so color names are
        properly reflected.

        * Sniffing on external scripts (-: that will also be verbose!

        * Indenting conditionals and nested scripts for extra clarity
        (useful when dealing with complex startups).

        * Converting  'QUIET' and 'NIL:' keywords on the fly so there
        is no need to alter the startup nor nested scripts.

        * Controling output of  background processes independently of
        redirection.

        * Prefixing  each line with valuable information such as time
        (elapsed, current) or caller address. See  configuration file
        for more options.

        * Using different than CON: console handlers such as KCON: or
        VNC:.

        * Disabling 68040/68060 data caches if support library is not 
        present so reliable operation can be expected. Caches will be
        turned on by the 'SetPatch'!

        * Logging boot  history to a file  as it happens. This can be
        SER: device too and thus remote terminal.

        * Logging to built-in circular buffer that is user definable.
        It is possible to review output of background processes after
        Workbench is up.

        * Muting  the keyboard per screen  so programs that catch raw
        key events perform as if no screen was opened.

        * Showing nice progress bar instead of script flow if told to
        do so.

        * Slowing  down script flow at  desired line to take a closer
        look at what is happening after command(s) did end.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



@node Req "qboot - Requirements"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      As every program  'qboot'  needs some minimal environment so it
      can run properly. Setup of,

        - Amiga with OS 3.x
        - M 68020+ processor
        - 1 M of chip memory

      is perhaps what will make it work. At least stock Amiga 1200 is
      OK. But for better user experience,

        - Amiga with OS 3.x
        - M 68030+ processor
        - 4 M of fast memory

      is recommended. Although this software was only tested under OS
      3.x it may still work on 2.x. Development setup is as follows,

        - Amiga 1200/OS 3.1
        - Apollo 1260/50 Mhz
        - 64 M of fast mem.
        - Micronik Zorro II
        - CVision 64/3D/4 M

      As to test systems second Amiga 1200 was used in configurations
      ranging from stock through,

        - Amiga 1200/OS 3.0
        - 8 M fast memory

      to another Apollo accelerator,

        - Amiga 1200/OS 3.0
        - Apollo 1240/33 Mhz
        - 32 M fast memory

      Software continues to work without  noticable problems on these
      machines so there is a chance that it will also work for you.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



@node Install "qboot - Installation"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      As  to installation it is as easy  as can be. First thing to do
      is to:

        cd qboot-1.07
        copy qboot qboot.conf #?.loco S:

      Then you will have to edit your  'startup-sequence'  using your
      favourite text editor and blast this in the very first line:

        S:qboot "****"      ; <--- OS 3.0 and below friendly this way
        C:SetPatch QUIET
        ...

      Yes,  there are two  asterisks (typed in a shell compatible way
      so  that everything is quirkless even under  39.xxx  and less)!
      Single  asterisk means  current input while two asterisks  mean
      current script. Basically,  prog will  takeover the  startup in
      order for itself. And no,  startup will  not be  attempted once
      again after 'qboot' is done.

      No other changes are necessary. You can even mess up config and
      your  Amiga will still  boot,  although the  old way. Fail-safe
      beast.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



@node Config "qboot - Configuration"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      I'm glad you are reading this because customisation is the most
      important  thing! You will however not  be given an explanation
      of all the  options here. Instead, open 'qboot.conf'  with some
      text editor  and follow small  reference  manual in there. This
      way I do not have to double the information and you do not have
      to go back to AmigaGuide document when in doubt.

      Below you will find some info on 'qboot' command line interface
      which is not explained anywhere else.

         > qboot ?

           FROM/A,CONF


         FROM/A   -   AmigaShell compatible script file. Pass '*' for
                      current input or  '**'  for current script when
                      program is a part of the script launched by the
                      OS.

         CONF     -   Optional configuration file. By default it will
                      be read from 'S:qboot.conf'.

      By default 'qboot.conf' is preset in such a way that 'qboot' is
      able to utilise your double monitor setup - MULTI/VGA/CGX/P96.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



@node FAQ "qboot - FAQ"
      ---------------------------------------------------------------

      This  section is relatively new. It was  created to help you in
      case you do not know something. Feel free to ask questions that
      are not answered here.


        1  Can I use '*e' instead of raw ESC code inside config file?

            Yes, you can. As of 1.05  '*e' abbreviation is being used
            by default.


        2  Can I access  the rollover  buffer that holds boot history
           without ANSI styles and colors and how?

            Yes. That is  indeed possible. Go  to the shell  and type
            something  like this  (where 16384  is the actual size of
            your rollover as defined in the configuration file):

            > echo >"QBOOT0:log DF *"ROLLOVER = 16384*" SA 1"
            > type QBOOT0:log


        3  Hey man, I have got a  problem with double asterisk input!
           The shell wants to execute '*'. What the phuck?

            You are probably using ROM  39.xxx and less. In such case
            try: "****" - four asterisks that are quoted.


        4  I seem to have difficulties with the ID=MODEID/K template.
           Where to get the detailed explanation of this interface?

            Please  download lastest  'qdev'  binary archive or visit
            its WWW and read the doc. called  'qdev_findgfxentry.txt'
            or 'FGE' for short.


        5  The prog. does not open any screen what could be the cause
           of that?

            Make  sure  that the  ID=MODEID/K  contains  a query that
            describes screenmode your machine is capable of.


        6  I would like to make my own LOGO but I lack information on
           how to do that. Where to find it?

            First of all, you will need 'qdev' and the compiler. They
            both can be grabbed from Aminet. Visit 'qdev' website for
            a shortcut. Nextly you will need 'Personal Paint' 7.x. It
            should also be on Aminet. Then follow the  FAQ chapter in
            'qdev' manual.


        7  I did notice  that there are commands that read backwards.
           Is that a bug?

            No :-), these are command replacements 'qboot' has to use
            it order to function properly.


        8  My  'startup-sequence' seems to malfunction under  'qboot'
           but seems  to work perfectly fine  without it. Can  I send
           you my startup file for further investigation?

            Yes, please  as this is  probably the  only way to figure
            out what could be wrong.

      ---------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode



